<DocsLayout title="Terminal Multiplexer" toc={toc}>

  <h1>Terminal Multiplexer</h1>

  <p>
    Training a neural network can take hours or days. If your SSH connection drops —
    due to a network hiccup, a laptop going to sleep, or a VPN timeout — any process
    running directly in your terminal will be killed. <strong>tmux</strong> solves this
    by running your shell sessions on the server, completely independent of your connection.
  </p>

  <!-- ── Why tmux ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="why">Why tmux?</h2>

  <p>
    tmux is a <em>terminal multiplexer</em>: it lets you create persistent sessions on the
    server, split your terminal into panes, and detach from a session without terminating
    the processes inside it. You can reconnect from a different machine and find everything
    exactly as you left it.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Persistence</strong> — processes survive SSH disconnections.</li>
    <li><strong>Organisation</strong> — separate windows for monitoring, experiments, and file navigation.</li>
    <li><strong>Collaboration</strong> — multiple people can attach to the same session (useful for debugging with a supervisor).</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ── Quick Start ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="quickstart">Quick Start</h2>

  <p>
    The key concept: <kbd>Ctrl-b</kbd> is the <em>prefix</em> — you press it before
    every tmux command. Release it, then press the next key.
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="bash"
    filename="westworld"
    code={`# Create a named session (use a meaningful name, e.g. your project)
tmux new -s resnet_training

# Inside the session, start your experiment as normal
python train.py --epochs 100 --gpu 0

# Detach from the session (your experiment keeps running!)
# Press: Ctrl-b  then  d

# Later, reattach from any SSH session
tmux attach -t resnet_training`}
  />

  <!-- ── Sessions ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="sessions">Managing Sessions</h2>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Action</th><th>Command</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Create a new named session</td><td><code>tmux new -s name</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td>List all sessions</td><td><code>tmux ls</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td>Attach to a session</td><td><code>tmux attach -t name</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td>Detach from current session</td><td><kbd>Ctrl-b</kbd> <kbd>d</kbd></td></tr>
      <tr><td>Rename current session</td><td><kbd>Ctrl-b</kbd> <kbd>$</kbd></td></tr>
      <tr><td>Kill a session</td><td><code>tmux kill-session -t name</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td>Kill all sessions</td><td><code>tmux kill-server</code></td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <div class="callout callout-warning">
    <svg class="w-5 h-5 flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5 text-yellow-500" fill="none" stroke="currentColor"
         stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
      <path d="M10.29 3.86L1.82 18a2 2 0 0 0 1.71 3h16.94a2 2 0 0 0 1.71-3L13.71 3.86a2 2 0 0 0-3.42 0z"/>
      <line x1="12" y1="9" x2="12" y2="13"/><line x1="12" y1="17" x2="12.01" y2="17"/>
    </svg>
    <div class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
      <strong>Clean up after yourself.</strong> When an experiment finishes, kill the session
      with <code>tmux kill-session -t name</code>. Leaving dozens of idle sessions clutters
      the server and can confuse colleagues checking what jobs are running.
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ── Windows & Panes ────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="windows-panes">Windows & Panes</h2>

  <p>
    A session can have multiple <em>windows</em> (like browser tabs), and each window
    can be split into <em>panes</em> (side-by-side or stacked terminals).
  </p>

  <h3>Windows</h3>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Action</th><th>Shortcut</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Create a new window</td><td><kbd>Ctrl-b</kbd> <kbd>c</kbd></td></tr>
      <tr><td>Switch to window by number</td><td><kbd>Ctrl-b</kbd> <kbd>0–9</kbd></td></tr>
      <tr><td>Next window</td><td><kbd>Ctrl-b</kbd> <kbd>n</kbd></td></tr>
      <tr><td>Previous window</td><td><kbd>Ctrl-b</kbd> <kbd>p</kbd></td></tr>
      <tr><td>Rename current window</td><td><kbd>Ctrl-b</kbd> <kbd>,</kbd></td></tr>
      <tr><td>Close current window</td><td><kbd>Ctrl-b</kbd> <kbd>&amp;</kbd></td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3>Panes</h3>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Action</th><th>Shortcut</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Split horizontally (side by side)</td><td><kbd>Ctrl-b</kbd> <kbd>%</kbd></td></tr>
      <tr><td>Split vertically (top/bottom)</td><td><kbd>Ctrl-b</kbd> <kbd>"</kbd></td></tr>
      <tr><td>Move between panes</td><td><kbd>Ctrl-b</kbd> <kbd>↑↓←→</kbd></td></tr>
      <tr><td>Resize pane</td><td><kbd>Ctrl-b</kbd> then hold <kbd>↑↓←→</kbd></td></tr>
      <tr><td>Zoom a pane to full screen</td><td><kbd>Ctrl-b</kbd> <kbd>z</kbd></td></tr>
      <tr><td>Close current pane</td><td><kbd>Ctrl-b</kbd> <kbd>x</kbd></td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <!-- ── Practical Workflow ──────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="workflow">Practical Workflow</h2>

  <p>
    A typical setup for a training run uses three windows within one session:
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="bash"
    filename="westworld — inside tmux"
    code={`# Create a session named after your experiment
tmux new -s yolo_finetune

# Window 0 (auto-created): run the training job
# Rename it for clarity: Ctrl-b ,  → type "train" → Enter
python train.py --config configs/yolo_v8.yaml --gpu 0

# Open a new window for monitoring: Ctrl-b c
# Rename it: Ctrl-b ,  → type "monitor" → Enter
# Split it into two panes: Ctrl-b %
watch -n 2 nvidia-smi           # left pane: GPU stats
htop                            # right pane (Ctrl-b → →): CPU/RAM

# Open a third window for file ops: Ctrl-b c
# Rename: Ctrl-b ,  → type "shell" → Enter
# Navigate outputs, edit configs, etc.
ls -lh outputs/`}
  />

  <p>
    Detach at any time with <kbd>Ctrl-b</kbd> <kbd>d</kbd>. Your training run continues.
    Reattach hours later from home with <code>ssh airlab</code> then
    <code>tmux attach -t yolo_finetune</code>.
  </p>

  <!-- ── Configuration ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="config">Configuration</h2>

  <p>
    tmux is highly configurable via <code>~/.tmux.conf</code>. The following settings
    make it significantly more comfortable to use:
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="bash"
    filename="~/.tmux.conf"
    code={`# Change prefix from Ctrl-b to Ctrl-a (optional, feels closer to screen)
# set -g prefix C-a
# unbind C-b
# bind C-a send-prefix

# Enable mouse support (click to select panes/windows, scroll history)
set -g mouse on

# Start window and pane numbering at 1 (not 0)
set -g base-index 1
set -g pane-base-index 1

# Increase scrollback history
set -g history-limit 50000

# Faster key repetition
set -sg escape-time 0

# Reload config with: Ctrl-b r
bind r source-file ~/.tmux.conf \; display-message "Config reloaded"

# Intuitive pane splitting (use current directory)
bind | split-window -h -c "#{pane_current_path}"
bind - split-window -v -c "#{pane_current_path}"

# Status bar: show session name, window list, time
set -g status-right '%H:%M %d-%b'
set -g status-style 'bg=#102c53 fg=white'
set -g window-status-current-style 'bold'`}
  />

  <p>
    After editing, reload the config without restarting tmux:
  </p>

  <CodeBlock lang="bash" code={`# Inside a tmux session:
tmux source-file ~/.tmux.conf

# Or with the binding above: Ctrl-b r`} />

</DocsLayout>
